00:00:19.458 --> 00:00:21.750 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: For a man
who holds his cards pretty

00:00:21.750 --> 00:00:23.760 align:middle line:10%
close to his chest,
Billy Carson and I

00:00:23.760 --> 00:00:26.190 align:middle line:10%
had a pretty
freewheeling conversation

00:00:26.190 --> 00:00:28.110 align:middle line:10%
about his years
growing up and what

00:00:28.110 --> 00:00:31.260 align:middle line:10%
influenced him to be so dogged
in his pursuit of truth.

00:00:31.260 --> 00:00:32.910 align:middle line:84%
Today, we're going
to dive even deeper

00:00:32.910 --> 00:00:36.030 align:middle line:84%
into his family's backstory,
which we did not have time

00:00:36.030 --> 00:00:37.800 align:middle line:90%
to do in the last conversation.

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:40.920 align:middle line:84%
It is not your normal
family history.

00:00:40.920 --> 00:00:41.820 align:middle line:90%
Welcome back, Billy.

00:00:41.820 --> 00:00:42.840 align:middle line:84%
>>BILLY CARSON:
Thanks for having me.

00:00:42.840 --> 00:00:45.270 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We just started
talking after the show,

00:00:45.270 --> 00:00:49.260 align:middle line:84%
and I thought, oh my god,
why couldn't we get to that?

00:00:49.260 --> 00:00:53.100 align:middle line:84%
So now, you're a
representative of a bloodline

00:00:53.100 --> 00:00:56.845 align:middle line:84%
of people that's been tapped
in a really interesting way.

00:00:56.845 --> 00:00:57.645 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Yes.

00:00:57.645 --> 00:01:02.940 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And first of all,
let's do a tiny little recap.

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:06.990 align:middle line:84%
In our last conversation, you
initially grew up in New York,

00:01:06.990 --> 00:01:07.790 align:middle line:90%
as I recall?

00:01:07.790 --> 00:01:08.280 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Mm-hm.

00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:09.465 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And a
background of poverty?

00:01:09.465 --> 00:01:10.200 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Yeah.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:11.000 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Poverty.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:12.850 align:middle line:84%
And you ended up
moving to Florida.

00:01:12.850 --> 00:01:15.300 align:middle line:84%
And just a quick little
recap, but you're

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:17.750 align:middle line:90%
a very ingenious man.

00:01:17.750 --> 00:01:19.890 align:middle line:84%
And you're an entrepreneur,
and you figured out

00:01:19.890 --> 00:01:23.070 align:middle line:84%
a way to make life work
for you and, really,

00:01:23.070 --> 00:01:24.600 align:middle line:90%
with stunning results.

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:26.610 align:middle line:10%
Maybe just give a
little recap for us

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:28.710 align:middle line:10%
before we start going back
to grandma and grandpa.

00:01:28.710 --> 00:01:30.170 align:middle line:10%
>>CARSON: Sure, I'll
give you a quick summary.

00:01:30.170 --> 00:01:30.430 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:01:30.430 --> 00:01:33.150 align:middle line:10%
>>CARSON: Basically, I was
born in New York City in Queens

00:01:33.150 --> 00:01:35.130 align:middle line:10%
at Queens General Hospital.

00:01:35.130 --> 00:01:38.010 align:middle line:10%
I lived in New York in
Cambria Heights Queens

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:42.480 align:middle line:10%
just from the age of birth
until about seven years old,

00:01:42.480 --> 00:01:44.370 align:middle line:10%
moved to Miami, Florida.

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:46.530 align:middle line:84%
In Miami, Florida, we
lived in Opa-locka,

00:01:46.530 --> 00:01:49.470 align:middle line:84%
which is a very
impoverished city, still

00:01:49.470 --> 00:01:50.400 align:middle line:90%
to this current day.

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:53.090 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I just went there a
few weeks ago to check on the--

00:01:53.090 --> 00:01:56.220 align:middle line:84%
just memory sake, kind
of go down memory lane,

00:01:56.220 --> 00:01:58.230 align:middle line:84%
and I was like, wow,
this is pretty bad.

00:01:58.230 --> 00:01:59.610 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: How long since
you had been there?

00:01:59.610 --> 00:02:01.890 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: Probably, I would
say, about three or four years.

00:02:01.890 --> 00:02:02.190 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:02:02.190 --> 00:02:04.148 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: And every time
I go back, it's worse.

00:02:04.148 --> 00:02:08.100 align:middle line:84%
This time, I saw a
12-foot barbed wire gate

00:02:08.100 --> 00:02:10.680 align:middle line:84%
around the elementary
school that I went to,

00:02:10.680 --> 00:02:12.930 align:middle line:84%
where I started my
research and investigation

00:02:12.930 --> 00:02:14.910 align:middle line:90%
with the encyclopedias.

00:02:14.910 --> 00:02:17.280 align:middle line:84%
But at that house
that we were renting

00:02:17.280 --> 00:02:19.890 align:middle line:84%
there is where I saw a
UFO in my backyard-- fly

00:02:19.890 --> 00:02:21.240 align:middle line:90%
over my backyard.

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:24.510 align:middle line:84%
We lived close to an airport,
so I knew it wasn't an airplane.

00:02:24.510 --> 00:02:26.640 align:middle line:84%
And that triggered my
research and investigation

00:02:26.640 --> 00:02:28.267 align:middle line:90%
into aerospace.

00:02:28.267 --> 00:02:30.600 align:middle line:84%
So I would go to Rainbow Park
Elementary to the library,

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:33.100 align:middle line:84%
and I literally would take down
the Encyclopedia Britannicas

00:02:33.100 --> 00:02:34.530 align:middle line:90%
and start researching aerospace.

00:02:34.530 --> 00:02:35.400 align:middle line:90%
I started back then.

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:36.510 align:middle line:90%
It was like 1977.

00:02:36.510 --> 00:02:37.980 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: You were how old?

00:02:37.980 --> 00:02:38.880 align:middle line:90%
About eight, or--

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:40.000 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Seven years old.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:40.430 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Seven.

00:02:40.430 --> 00:02:40.670 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Yeah.

00:02:40.670 --> 00:02:41.030 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:41.410 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Yeah, seven years old.

00:02:41.410 --> 00:02:44.550 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: And just also, as
a little prehistory to that,

00:02:44.550 --> 00:02:48.240 align:middle line:10%
your dad was kind of taking
you out proud to show you off

00:02:48.240 --> 00:02:52.980 align:middle line:10%
when you were like two to the
bar to read out of the Bible

00:02:52.980 --> 00:02:54.390 align:middle line:10%
to his friends.

00:02:54.390 --> 00:02:55.830 align:middle line:10%
Look at how smart my kid is.

00:02:55.830 --> 00:02:58.813 align:middle line:84%
And he saw to it that your
family became very literate.

00:02:58.813 --> 00:02:59.730 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Yes, he did.

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:02.782 align:middle line:84%
That's one thing I've got
to give him the credit for,

00:03:02.782 --> 00:03:04.740 align:middle line:84%
even though it was a
weird experience going out

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:05.610 align:middle line:90%
to these bars.

00:03:05.610 --> 00:03:08.670 align:middle line:84%
And then, he'd come home and
watch my mom clobber him.

00:03:08.670 --> 00:03:11.237 align:middle line:84%
But I was reading novels
at the age of one.

00:03:11.237 --> 00:03:13.070 align:middle line:84%
I was reading children's
books at 10 months,

00:03:13.070 --> 00:03:14.112 align:middle line:90%
novels at the age of one.

00:03:14.112 --> 00:03:16.140 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That
sounds like a myth.

00:03:16.140 --> 00:03:19.970 align:middle line:84%
It's like, how can you even
process information at one

00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:24.210 align:middle line:84%
unless the way you came in was
already wired developmentally

00:03:24.210 --> 00:03:26.142 align:middle line:84%
completely differently
than your normal human.

00:03:26.142 --> 00:03:27.600 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: I was a
little different.

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:30.030 align:middle line:84%
From early on, I knew that I
was a little bit different, just

00:03:30.030 --> 00:03:31.560 align:middle line:84%
because of the things
that I would retain,

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:32.985 align:middle line:84%
and how I would
know information,

00:03:32.985 --> 00:03:34.110 align:middle line:90%
and how I would see things.

00:03:34.110 --> 00:03:36.420 align:middle line:84%
And other kids that
I would interact with

00:03:36.420 --> 00:03:38.550 align:middle line:84%
didn't have the same
concepts that I had

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:39.950 align:middle line:90%
or perceptions that I had.

00:03:39.950 --> 00:03:42.515 align:middle line:84%
And I realized early on that
in some kind of way in my mind

00:03:42.515 --> 00:03:43.890 align:middle line:84%
they were a little
bit behind me,

00:03:43.890 --> 00:03:46.350 align:middle line:84%
but I was just actually a
little bit ahead of them.

00:03:46.350 --> 00:03:47.940 align:middle line:84%
When I got to Rainbow
Park Elementary,

00:03:47.940 --> 00:03:51.630 align:middle line:84%
more verifiable information,
they asked my mom if I wanted

00:03:51.630 --> 00:03:54.597 align:middle line:84%
to go to kindergarten and
just be in kindergarten--

00:03:54.597 --> 00:03:56.430 align:middle line:84%
because I hadn't been
to school yet at all--

00:03:56.430 --> 00:03:58.290 align:middle line:84%
or if I wanted to go
to the second grade.

00:03:58.290 --> 00:04:00.300 align:middle line:84%
And she said, just put
him in the first grade.

00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:02.640 align:middle line:84%
Give him a chance to acclimate
with the kids and everything

00:04:02.640 --> 00:04:03.190 align:middle line:90%
else.

00:04:03.190 --> 00:04:05.100 align:middle line:84%
But I could've went straight
to the second grade.

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:06.510 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Well, that
makes sense because,

00:04:06.510 --> 00:04:08.140 align:middle line:10%
well, you probably
could have gone

00:04:08.140 --> 00:04:10.020 align:middle line:10%
to the fifth or sixth
grade academically.

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:11.820 align:middle line:84%
But socially, you'd
have been way out

00:04:11.820 --> 00:04:14.250 align:middle line:84%
of sync and under
influences of older kids.

00:04:14.250 --> 00:04:17.040 align:middle line:10%
So then as you started
becoming a young man,

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:20.310 align:middle line:10%
you became involved in
and fascinated with--

00:04:20.310 --> 00:04:23.010 align:middle line:10%
was it digital that was
coming up at the time?

00:04:23.010 --> 00:04:24.620 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: Yeah,
digital car stereo.

00:04:24.620 --> 00:04:27.780 align:middle line:84%
So in my dad's car, he
had 8-track players.

00:04:27.780 --> 00:04:29.480 align:middle line:84%
One was a junker that
we had in the yard

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:31.810 align:middle line:84%
that we would take apart and
put back together for fun.

00:04:31.810 --> 00:04:32.610 align:middle line:90%
The other one--

00:04:32.610 --> 00:04:33.720 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Never thought of that.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:35.880 align:middle line:84%
That's a great way to learn
mechanical engineering, right?

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:36.540 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Absolutely.

00:04:36.540 --> 00:04:37.340 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:04:37.340 --> 00:04:40.140 align:middle line:84%
And the other one was his car,
which worked from time to time,

00:04:40.140 --> 00:04:41.580 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS] but it had an 8-track.

00:04:41.580 --> 00:04:43.955 align:middle line:84%
With 8-tracks, as you know,
anybody who knows about them,

00:04:43.955 --> 00:04:45.300 align:middle line:90%
you can't rewind.

00:04:45.300 --> 00:04:46.820 align:middle line:84%
It's always listen till the
end, then it starts over.

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:47.625 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It goes one direction.

00:04:47.625 --> 00:04:49.080 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: One direction.

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:50.790 align:middle line:84%
And I started
researching you know

00:04:50.790 --> 00:04:52.218 align:middle line:90%
into what's coming up next.

00:04:52.218 --> 00:04:53.760 align:middle line:84%
I knew this couldn't
persist forever.

00:04:53.760 --> 00:04:55.030 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And how old
were you at this point?

00:04:55.030 --> 00:04:56.220 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: I was 12 years old.

00:04:56.220 --> 00:04:56.470 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:04:56.470 --> 00:04:57.845 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: Yeah,
And I was selling

00:04:57.845 --> 00:04:59.307 align:middle line:90%
newspapers for the Miami news.

00:04:59.307 --> 00:05:01.890 align:middle line:84%
So I would take the money that
I was making from my commission

00:05:01.890 --> 00:05:04.290 align:middle line:84%
from selling subscriptions
and I found a company called

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:05.813 align:middle line:90%
"Galaxy Electronics."

00:05:05.813 --> 00:05:07.230 align:middle line:84%
They were inside
and, still today,

00:05:07.230 --> 00:05:09.030 align:middle line:84%
are inside of the
Opportunity magazine

00:05:09.030 --> 00:05:11.240 align:middle line:84%
that you can get in
the grocery store.

00:05:11.240 --> 00:05:13.930 align:middle line:84%
Mine was at Winn-Dixie grocery
store right around the corner.

00:05:13.930 --> 00:05:14.730 align:middle line:90%
I would go there.

00:05:14.730 --> 00:05:16.450 align:middle line:90%
I got the Opportunity book.

00:05:16.450 --> 00:05:17.850 align:middle line:90%
And I found this company.

00:05:17.850 --> 00:05:20.280 align:middle line:84%
I started looking at all the
radios they were coming out

00:05:20.280 --> 00:05:21.390 align:middle line:90%
with and electronics.

00:05:21.390 --> 00:05:23.340 align:middle line:84%
I started buying
digital car radios

00:05:23.340 --> 00:05:27.150 align:middle line:84%
with cassette decks and also
EQ boosters and, even then,

00:05:27.150 --> 00:05:28.860 align:middle line:90%
eventually subwoofers.

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:32.112 align:middle line:84%
And I had, eventually, the
largest electronics company

00:05:32.112 --> 00:05:33.570 align:middle line:84%
pretty much in the
tri-county area.

00:05:33.570 --> 00:05:35.445 align:middle line:84%
People were coming from
all over the counties

00:05:35.445 --> 00:05:37.165 align:middle line:84%
to come to my house
to buy because nobody

00:05:37.165 --> 00:05:38.040 align:middle line:90%
could beat my prices.

00:05:38.040 --> 00:05:40.470 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: At the ripe
old age of, what, 13, 14?

00:05:40.470 --> 00:05:41.510 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: 13, yeah.

00:05:41.510 --> 00:05:42.450 align:middle line:90%
By then, I was 13.

00:05:42.450 --> 00:05:43.908 align:middle line:84%
By the time I was
14, I was already

00:05:43.908 --> 00:05:45.500 align:middle line:90%
making more than my parents.

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:46.770 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: I love it.

00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:47.740 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:05:47.740 --> 00:05:51.065 align:middle line:84%
And meanwhile, you were still
continuing your research?

00:05:51.065 --> 00:05:52.440 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: Yes,
still researching.

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:56.730 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --regarding reverse
propulsion technologies

00:05:56.730 --> 00:06:01.110 align:middle line:84%
and anti-gravity technologies,
trying to piece together

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:04.110 align:middle line:84%
how that experience you
had functioned physically

00:06:04.110 --> 00:06:05.460 align:middle line:90%
in the physical world, right?

00:06:05.460 --> 00:06:06.120 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Right, exactly.

00:06:06.120 --> 00:06:07.495 align:middle line:84%
I got into all
types of sciences.

00:06:07.495 --> 00:06:10.050 align:middle line:84%
The great thing that happened,
universal synchronicity,

00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:13.180 align:middle line:84%
I guess, is not too long
after that experience--

00:06:13.180 --> 00:06:15.740 align:middle line:84%
and I was researching
the encyclopedias,

00:06:15.740 --> 00:06:17.700 align:middle line:84%
the encyclopedia
salesperson came to my house

00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:21.480 align:middle line:84%
knocking on the door, and my mom
got approved for the whole set.

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:22.530 align:middle line:90%
So I was in heaven then.

00:06:22.530 --> 00:06:23.340 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, yeah.

00:06:23.340 --> 00:06:28.800 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: So I was studying
biology, physics, aerospace,

00:06:28.800 --> 00:06:31.180 align:middle line:84%
everything you could
think of that existed--

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:33.570 align:middle line:84%
economies, and history--
everything that

00:06:33.570 --> 00:06:34.830 align:middle line:90%
was in those books.

00:06:34.830 --> 00:06:35.630 align:middle line:90%
It was incredible.

00:06:35.630 --> 00:06:38.770 align:middle line:84%
And I was, like, buried in those
books from morning till night.

00:06:38.770 --> 00:06:40.020 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: How did that happen?

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:41.370 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: Well,
at that time, they

00:06:41.370 --> 00:06:43.290 align:middle line:84%
were so desperate to get
books out, it was like,

00:06:43.290 --> 00:06:44.400 align:middle line:84%
we're going to give
you these books,

00:06:44.400 --> 00:06:46.410 align:middle line:84%
and you gotta pay X amount
of dollars every week.

00:06:46.410 --> 00:06:46.890 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:06:46.890 --> 00:06:49.080 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: And she started
off giving them the money

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:49.440 align:middle line:90%
every week.

00:06:49.440 --> 00:06:51.523 align:middle line:84%
Eventually, she wasn't
able to pay for it anymore.

00:06:51.523 --> 00:06:54.030 align:middle line:84%
But what happened was
the salespeople never

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:55.455 align:middle line:90%
came back knocking on the door.

00:06:55.455 --> 00:06:56.850 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And they didn't
take their set back?

00:06:56.850 --> 00:06:57.750 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: They
didn't take it back.

00:06:57.750 --> 00:06:59.150 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That was
your real education?

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:01.170 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: That was my
in-home education, period.

00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:03.900 align:middle line:84%
Literally, that's
what got me started.

00:07:03.900 --> 00:07:06.150 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: So now, as
your story progressed,

00:07:06.150 --> 00:07:09.060 align:middle line:10%
you stayed very
entrepreneurial and successful,

00:07:09.060 --> 00:07:11.370 align:middle line:10%
and you have a very disciplined
way about you in mind,

00:07:11.370 --> 00:07:13.770 align:middle line:10%
and athletics also
factors into your family.

00:07:13.770 --> 00:07:16.470 align:middle line:10%
You're a disciplined person.

00:07:16.470 --> 00:07:22.110 align:middle line:10%
You were able to retire, as I
recall, at a very young age,

00:07:22.110 --> 00:07:24.520 align:middle line:10%
and raise your little kids,
and really be there for them.

00:07:24.520 --> 00:07:25.320 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Yeah.

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:26.945 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Talk about
that a little bit.

00:07:26.945 --> 00:07:28.830 align:middle line:84%
Did you end up retiring
from that company

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:30.000 align:middle line:90%
or another subsequent one?

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.583 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: It was from a company
called Dotcom Marketing Group.

00:07:32.583 --> 00:07:35.610 align:middle line:84%
So basically, I saw,
again, the future.

00:07:35.610 --> 00:07:37.110 align:middle line:90%
I have a futuristic mindset.

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:39.930 align:middle line:84%
I always see things,
what's going to be next.

00:07:39.930 --> 00:07:41.200 align:middle line:90%
And I saw a commercial.

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:43.575 align:middle line:84%
That's all you need, a small
glimpse of a commercial that

00:07:43.575 --> 00:07:45.040 align:middle line:90%
said, "IBM.com."

00:07:45.040 --> 00:07:46.053 align:middle line:90%
And I said "dot com?"

00:07:46.053 --> 00:07:48.720 align:middle line:84%
And the commercial was talking a
little bit about the internet--

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:49.985 align:middle line:90%
not too much.

00:07:49.985 --> 00:07:51.360 align:middle line:84%
So I said, what
is this internet?

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:53.490 align:middle line:84%
So I started looking
into the internet.

00:07:53.490 --> 00:07:55.710 align:middle line:90%
This was like 1998.

00:07:55.710 --> 00:07:58.500 align:middle line:84%
A few companies had
websites, and that was it.

00:07:58.500 --> 00:08:00.490 align:middle line:84%
And I said, wow,
eventually, everybody's

00:08:00.490 --> 00:08:01.710 align:middle line:90%
going to want one of these.

00:08:01.710 --> 00:08:04.590 align:middle line:84%
And ironically-- again, the
universe works in mysterious

00:08:04.590 --> 00:08:05.460 align:middle line:90%
ways--

00:08:05.460 --> 00:08:09.050 align:middle line:84%
two weeks later,
one of the gentleman

00:08:09.050 --> 00:08:11.040 align:middle line:84%
that lived in my
same community, he

00:08:11.040 --> 00:08:12.540 align:middle line:84%
was an exchange
student from Arabia.

00:08:12.540 --> 00:08:14.248 align:middle line:84%
And he said to me, do
you have a company?

00:08:14.248 --> 00:08:17.010 align:middle line:84%
Because I need to make
a website for a company

00:08:17.010 --> 00:08:18.360 align:middle line:90%
as part of my internship.

00:08:18.360 --> 00:08:19.985 align:middle line:84%
And I was like, yeah,
I have a company,

00:08:19.985 --> 00:08:21.650 align:middle line:84%
and I was looking
to make websites.

00:08:21.650 --> 00:08:22.650 align:middle line:90%
I sat over his shoulder.

00:08:22.650 --> 00:08:23.885 align:middle line:90%
I watched everything he did.

00:08:23.885 --> 00:08:26.010 align:middle line:84%
And then when he got done,
I went to Rent-A-Center,

00:08:26.010 --> 00:08:27.805 align:middle line:90%
I got a Packet From Hell.

00:08:27.805 --> 00:08:29.428 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: What's at
packet from hell?

00:08:29.428 --> 00:08:30.470 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: A Packard Bell.

00:08:30.470 --> 00:08:31.562 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, a Packard Bell.

00:08:31.562 --> 00:08:31.960 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:33.710 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: We called
it at Packet from Hell

00:08:33.710 --> 00:08:35.280 align:middle line:90%
because it crashed all the time.

00:08:35.280 --> 00:08:36.080 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK, good.

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:39.340 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: Two gigabyte
hard drive, AOL dial up,

00:08:39.340 --> 00:08:41.340 align:middle line:84%
and I started replicating
what I saw him doing.

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:43.020 align:middle line:84%
And when I realized I
had a talent for it,

00:08:43.020 --> 00:08:44.910 align:middle line:84%
I went to the bookstore
and I would just literally

00:08:44.910 --> 00:08:47.243 align:middle line:84%
read the books at the bookstore,
take a couple of notes,

00:08:47.243 --> 00:08:48.790 align:middle line:90%
go home, and duplicate it.

00:08:48.790 --> 00:08:49.590 align:middle line:90%
And I said, wow.

00:08:49.590 --> 00:08:52.020 align:middle line:84%
Now if I can make a website
for a service-based company,

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:54.187 align:middle line:84%
I can just make the same
website over and over again

00:08:54.187 --> 00:08:55.771 align:middle line:84%
and change the colors
and the content,

00:08:55.771 --> 00:08:57.477 align:middle line:90%
and I can do well with this.

00:08:57.477 --> 00:08:59.310 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So you had
to teach yourself code?

00:08:59.310 --> 00:09:01.477 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: I taught myself
five different programming

00:09:01.477 --> 00:09:03.747 align:middle line:84%
languages, yes,
from the bookstore.

00:09:03.747 --> 00:09:06.080 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: See, I just like
hearing this story over again

00:09:06.080 --> 00:09:08.338 align:middle line:84%
because I'm so
awe-inspired all the time.

00:09:08.338 --> 00:09:09.630 align:middle line:90%
I just want to keep hearing it.

00:09:09.630 --> 00:09:09.960 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:09:09.960 --> 00:09:11.260 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: And that's what I did.

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:12.802 align:middle line:84%
So I started Dot
Com Marketing Group.

00:09:12.802 --> 00:09:15.360 align:middle line:84%
I started telemarketing
mortgage companies

00:09:15.360 --> 00:09:16.868 align:middle line:90%
Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday.

00:09:16.868 --> 00:09:19.160 align:middle line:84%
Thursday and Friday, I would
go out on the appointments

00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:21.350 align:middle line:84%
that I set for myself,
sell them the websites.

00:09:21.350 --> 00:09:23.070 align:middle line:84%
Saturday and Sunday, I
would put the websites up

00:09:23.070 --> 00:09:24.256 align:middle line:84%
and I would duplicate
their numbers.

00:09:24.256 --> 00:09:26.515 align:middle line:84%
I was doing, like, 10,000
hours a week doing that.

00:09:26.515 --> 00:09:27.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, my God.

00:09:27.390 --> 00:09:28.190 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Yeah.

00:09:28.190 --> 00:09:29.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And so
when it was time,

00:09:29.820 --> 00:09:31.410 align:middle line:90%
you said, OK, I've done this.

00:09:31.410 --> 00:09:34.272 align:middle line:84%
And you had enough money to
retire well in good style.

00:09:34.272 --> 00:09:35.730 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: Yeah,
well, what happened

00:09:35.730 --> 00:09:37.775 align:middle line:84%
was a gentleman
approached me who

00:09:37.775 --> 00:09:39.900 align:middle line:84%
owned this company called
"Glow Bench Systems," who

00:09:39.900 --> 00:09:42.240 align:middle line:84%
were on the pink sheets
on the stock market.

00:09:42.240 --> 00:09:44.400 align:middle line:84%
And he said, we need
a cash-rich company

00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:48.360 align:middle line:84%
to add to our bottom line
so we can move up and then

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:50.250 align:middle line:90%
even maybe sell the company.

00:09:50.250 --> 00:09:51.870 align:middle line:84%
So they acquired
my company, which

00:09:51.870 --> 00:09:53.370 align:middle line:84%
the press release
is still available

00:09:53.370 --> 00:09:54.737 align:middle line:90%
online from all these years.

00:09:54.737 --> 00:09:56.320 align:middle line:84%
They acquired Dot.com
Marketing Group.

00:09:56.320 --> 00:09:59.700 align:middle line:84%
So I took that money,
and they acquired it.

00:09:59.700 --> 00:10:03.450 align:middle line:84%
They eventually sold to
the amber alert system.

00:10:03.450 --> 00:10:04.950 align:middle line:84%
They funded the
amber alert system,

00:10:04.950 --> 00:10:07.650 align:middle line:84%
and that's where it
ended up merging with.

00:10:07.650 --> 00:10:09.540 align:middle line:90%
But I took seven years off.

00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:11.790 align:middle line:84%
I didn't do anything, literally
could have stayed out.

00:10:11.790 --> 00:10:13.850 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: How lucky
your kids were.

00:10:13.850 --> 00:10:15.600 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: Oh, I stayed
with the kids all--

00:10:15.600 --> 00:10:18.527 align:middle line:84%
I spent so much
time with my kids--

00:10:18.527 --> 00:10:20.860 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there's no way even
that their mother can add up

00:10:20.860 --> 00:10:21.818 align:middle line:90%
to the amount of hours.

00:10:21.818 --> 00:10:22.990 align:middle line:90%
I was at every school.

00:10:22.990 --> 00:10:25.570 align:middle line:90%
I volunteered at every school--

00:10:25.570 --> 00:10:27.910 align:middle line:84%
all the sports, I
coach every sport,

00:10:27.910 --> 00:10:30.732 align:middle line:84%
I help build the
YMCA in West Broward.

00:10:30.732 --> 00:10:32.440 align:middle line:84%
When you walk in the
giant granite block,

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:33.820 align:middle line:90%
I'm a founding member.

00:10:33.820 --> 00:10:37.360 align:middle line:84%
I started all the sports
programs in Western Florida

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:40.240 align:middle line:84%
and, really, just helped
participate in any way I can.

00:10:40.240 --> 00:10:42.730 align:middle line:84%
I became a team USA
coach, Junior Olympics,

00:10:42.730 --> 00:10:44.900 align:middle line:84%
high school basketball
coach, gold medals, I mean,

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:46.320 align:middle line:90%
the whole thing.

00:10:46.320 --> 00:10:47.755 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, so it was amazing.

00:10:47.755 --> 00:10:50.370 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yeah, over-achiever
doesn't work right.

00:10:50.370 --> 00:10:52.850 align:middle line:90%
It doesn't really work for you.

00:10:52.850 --> 00:10:54.350 align:middle line:84%
You're in a category
of your own.

00:10:54.350 --> 00:10:57.995 align:middle line:90%


00:10:57.995 --> 00:11:00.370 align:middle line:10%
How did you get to the point
where they started featuring

00:11:00.370 --> 00:11:03.250 align:middle line:10%
you on shows, like what
you do here at Gaia,

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:06.128 align:middle line:10%
"Deep Space" and
"Ancient Civilizations,"

00:11:06.128 --> 00:11:07.420 align:middle line:10%
"Ancient Aliens," and all that.

00:11:07.420 --> 00:11:08.230 align:middle line:90%
How did that happen?

00:11:08.230 --> 00:11:09.772 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: You know,
it really started

00:11:09.772 --> 00:11:12.310 align:middle line:84%
when I started researching the
procession of the equinoxes.

00:11:12.310 --> 00:11:14.090 align:middle line:90%
I became an amateur astronomer.

00:11:14.090 --> 00:11:15.340 align:middle line:90%
And I started realizing that--

00:11:15.340 --> 00:11:15.710 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Of course.

00:11:15.710 --> 00:11:16.150 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: [LAUGHS] Of course.

00:11:16.150 --> 00:11:16.950 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:11:16.950 --> 00:11:18.660 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:22.163 align:middle line:84%
But I started realizing that
the procession was speeding up.

00:11:22.163 --> 00:11:24.580 align:middle line:84%
And I was like, what can cause
the procession to speed up?

00:11:24.580 --> 00:11:26.080 align:middle line:84%
And that took me
down a whole rabbit

00:11:26.080 --> 00:11:29.568 align:middle line:84%
hole of trying to figure out,
is our sun orbiting something?

00:11:29.568 --> 00:11:32.110 align:middle line:84%
Because we would need breakaway
speed if we were speeding up.

00:11:32.110 --> 00:11:33.943 align:middle line:84%
These are the questions
I was asking myself.

00:11:33.943 --> 00:11:36.490 align:middle line:84%
And I started finding potential
answers to those questions,

00:11:36.490 --> 00:11:38.350 align:middle line:84%
and I started looking
into the history books

00:11:38.350 --> 00:11:39.860 align:middle line:84%
and seeing where,
in ancient times,

00:11:39.860 --> 00:11:42.040 align:middle line:84%
according to this speed
up of the procession,

00:11:42.040 --> 00:11:44.770 align:middle line:84%
different geological disasters
were happening on Earth.

00:11:44.770 --> 00:11:46.390 align:middle line:84%
So I started thinking
that we could

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:49.063 align:middle line:84%
be orbiting another star in
our solar system, which now

00:11:49.063 --> 00:11:50.230 align:middle line:90%
has been officially proven--

00:11:50.230 --> 00:11:51.452 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:11:51.452 --> 00:11:52.660 align:middle line:90%
The binary star system, yeah.

00:11:52.660 --> 00:11:53.200 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Correct.

00:11:53.200 --> 00:11:54.742 align:middle line:84%
And I started
thinking, hmm, I should

00:11:54.742 --> 00:11:56.380 align:middle line:90%
make an underground shelter.

00:11:56.380 --> 00:11:58.090 align:middle line:84%
So I built an
underground shelter

00:11:58.090 --> 00:12:00.630 align:middle line:84%
about the size of three
Wal-Marts in Northwest Georgia.

00:12:00.630 --> 00:12:01.463 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Of course.

00:12:01.463 --> 00:12:02.671 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: [LAUGHS]

00:12:02.671 --> 00:12:05.004 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Can the rest of us
come when it all goes down?

00:12:05.004 --> 00:12:05.804 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:05.804 --> 00:12:06.720 align:middle line:90%
Go ahead.

00:12:06.720 --> 00:12:09.430 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: It's to save the
lives of 360 people in case

00:12:09.430 --> 00:12:11.898 align:middle line:84%
of a geological or
economic collapse.

00:12:11.898 --> 00:12:13.690 align:middle line:84%
And it got featured on
the History Channel,

00:12:13.690 --> 00:12:14.815 align:middle line:90%
so that was my first break.

00:12:14.815 --> 00:12:16.300 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Ah, OK.

00:12:16.300 --> 00:12:19.290 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: The History Channel
came down, the producers, they

00:12:19.290 --> 00:12:20.090 align:middle line:90%
talked to me.

00:12:20.090 --> 00:12:21.730 align:middle line:84%
They came to my
offices and everything.

00:12:21.730 --> 00:12:22.730 align:middle line:90%
It's still online today.

00:12:22.730 --> 00:12:24.630 align:middle line:84%
It's called the
Countdown to Apocalypse.

00:12:24.630 --> 00:12:26.455 align:middle line:84%
It's the episode
called Nostradamus.

00:12:26.455 --> 00:12:28.210 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Nostradamus, OK.

00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:31.120 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: And so that's
when I first got on TV.

00:12:31.120 --> 00:12:32.140 align:middle line:90%
I got an IMDb.

00:12:32.140 --> 00:12:33.072 align:middle line:90%
I got on IMDb.

00:12:33.072 --> 00:12:34.780 align:middle line:84%
And then other people
start looking me up

00:12:34.780 --> 00:12:36.340 align:middle line:84%
to see what I was into
and what I was doing,

00:12:36.340 --> 00:12:39.010 align:middle line:84%
and then it started turning
into radio shows and everything

00:12:39.010 --> 00:12:39.220 align:middle line:90%
else.

00:12:39.220 --> 00:12:40.510 align:middle line:84%
And I started finding
out all the other things

00:12:40.510 --> 00:12:42.885 align:middle line:84%
I was researching, and talking
about, and blogging about,

00:12:42.885 --> 00:12:45.772 align:middle line:84%
and writing up in forums, and
it just kept growing from there.

00:12:45.772 --> 00:12:46.970 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: So here we are.

00:12:46.970 --> 00:12:49.970 align:middle line:84%
And you don't generally
have the opportunity

00:12:49.970 --> 00:12:53.097 align:middle line:84%
in these various formats to talk
about your own personal story,

00:12:53.097 --> 00:12:55.430 align:middle line:84%
which is why I wanted to do
that with you because you're

00:12:55.430 --> 00:12:56.660 align:middle line:90%
an exceptional human being--

00:12:56.660 --> 00:12:57.000 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Thank you.

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:58.860 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --on
virtually every level.

00:12:58.860 --> 00:13:01.790 align:middle line:10%
And so we don't
have a chance to see

00:13:01.790 --> 00:13:04.850 align:middle line:10%
how the lives of people like you
are up close and personal that

00:13:04.850 --> 00:13:05.810 align:middle line:10%
often.

00:13:05.810 --> 00:13:10.160 align:middle line:10%
And so as we started speaking at
the end of our last interview,

00:13:10.160 --> 00:13:13.040 align:middle line:10%
it turns out it wasn't just you.

00:13:13.040 --> 00:13:13.840 align:middle line:10%
It's in your blood.

00:13:13.840 --> 00:13:14.260 align:middle line:10%
>>CARSON: Yeah.

00:13:14.260 --> 00:13:15.300 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:13:15.300 --> 00:13:19.850 align:middle line:10%
So let's start at the beginning
of your family's backstory

00:13:19.850 --> 00:13:22.570 align:middle line:10%
and probably with your
grandma and grandpa?

00:13:22.570 --> 00:13:23.370 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Yeah.

00:13:23.370 --> 00:13:25.955 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: OK,
paternal or maternal?

00:13:25.955 --> 00:13:26.850 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Paternal.

00:13:26.850 --> 00:13:28.260 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Paternal, OK.

00:13:28.260 --> 00:13:34.190 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: So my grandmother,
she is a Puerto Rican woman.

00:13:34.190 --> 00:13:35.740 align:middle line:90%
Her last name is de Castro.

00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:38.240 align:middle line:84%
So all the de Castros in Puerto
Rico are all related to me--

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:40.700 align:middle line:84%
or I'm related to
them, I should say.

00:13:40.700 --> 00:13:46.062 align:middle line:84%
And her grandmother was like a
princess almost in Puerto Rico.

00:13:46.062 --> 00:13:47.270 align:middle line:90%
This is a very long time ago.

00:13:47.270 --> 00:13:49.910 align:middle line:84%
My grandmother now is 97,
so it's been a long time.

00:13:49.910 --> 00:13:53.660 align:middle line:84%
I have a few great, great,
great aunts that are 103, 109,

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:55.100 align:middle line:90%
so forth, so long lifespans.

00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:58.910 align:middle line:84%
But she met my grandfather who
was from the St. Thomas Virgin

00:13:58.910 --> 00:14:01.910 align:middle line:84%
Islands, or The British Virgin
Islands, and they got together,

00:14:01.910 --> 00:14:07.700 align:middle line:84%
and she moved to St. Thomas
with him and started a family.

00:14:07.700 --> 00:14:09.770 align:middle line:84%
Now my grandfather's
side of the family

00:14:09.770 --> 00:14:12.050 align:middle line:84%
had been interacting
with people there,

00:14:12.050 --> 00:14:14.630 align:middle line:84%
as far as I know
now from my aunt who

00:14:14.630 --> 00:14:17.300 align:middle line:84%
told me this, from a
very long time ago.

00:14:17.300 --> 00:14:21.200 align:middle line:84%
In ancient times, she told
me that people that were more

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:22.430 align:middle line:90%
advanced than us--

00:14:22.430 --> 00:14:24.320 align:middle line:90%
she didn't say aliens--

00:14:24.320 --> 00:14:28.010 align:middle line:84%
were involved in building
structures on this planet

00:14:28.010 --> 00:14:30.920 align:middle line:84%
and that our family
would aid them

00:14:30.920 --> 00:14:33.390 align:middle line:90%
with the construction process.

00:14:33.390 --> 00:14:34.250 align:middle line:90%
And I was like, wow.

00:14:34.250 --> 00:14:36.500 align:middle line:84%
Now she's basically
almost dead now.

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:38.450 align:middle line:90%
She's about to pass away soon.

00:14:38.450 --> 00:14:40.340 align:middle line:84%
She contacted me
and said that this

00:14:40.340 --> 00:14:42.090 align:middle line:84%
is something I want to tell
you before I leave this Earth.

00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:43.720 align:middle line:84%
Now she doesn't know anything
about Forbidden Knowledge,

00:14:43.720 --> 00:14:44.720 align:middle line:90%
me being on TV--

00:14:44.720 --> 00:14:46.480 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: She doesn't know
anything about your life?

00:14:46.480 --> 00:14:47.490 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: No, nothing.

00:14:47.490 --> 00:14:49.755 align:middle line:84%
She knows nothing, not even
an email or a cell phone.

00:14:49.755 --> 00:14:51.430 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Just that you did
well financially, that's it.

00:14:51.430 --> 00:14:53.250 align:middle line:84%
>>CARSON: I did
well financially--

00:14:53.250 --> 00:14:56.540 align:middle line:84%
her son tells her,
oh, Billy's doing OK.

00:14:56.540 --> 00:15:00.710 align:middle line:84%
And my mom passed
away nine years ago.

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:03.510 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Now we'll get
into that in a minute,

00:15:03.510 --> 00:15:06.900 align:middle line:84%
but your mother always
understood your curiosity about

00:15:06.900 --> 00:15:07.700 align:middle line:90%
these things--

00:15:07.700 --> 00:15:08.100 align:middle line:90%
>>CARSON: Oh, absolutely.

